The passengers and crew of the diamond princess are being rescued via social media. Each person, each party, in this case, has their own demands and positions.

On February 11, a family of three waved to their family members who were trapped on a cruise ship. Photograph by Carl Court Getty

Social media has become an important channel for passengers to communicate with the outside world during this cruise infection.

In a departure from previous disaster responses, the isolated passengers used the network to form a support group.

Media that can not access the scene become "exploited" . Passengers Broadcast "News" through a variety of technical means, they have even learned to use the media to complete supervision, the realization of demand.

Rules for handling emergencies can mean either order or more cumbersome processes.

On Feb. 13, about 3,000 people aboard the luxury cruise ship diamond princess were still untested for the virus. There have been 217 confirmed cases with a quarantine officer and about 3,400 sealed aboard.

The ship, carrying 3,711 people, set out from Yokohama, Japan, via Kagoshima, Hong Kong, Da Nang, Geelong and Naha, and is scheduled to return to Yokohama on February 4. But things changed along the way. After January 30, the passengers began to realize that they could not get off the ship.

On February 6 th, the diamond princess was docked in Port of Yokohama, Japan. Photograph: AP
On February 5, the Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare (similar to the "Ministry of Health" in our understanding) confirmed that 10 of the ship's first 31 suspected cases had been diagnosed with pneumonia caused by COVID-19, and that none of them could go ashore, must be quarantined on board for 14 days. The contagion chain was triggered by an 80-year-old man who had spent five days on the ship. Although he had left the ship after his journey on 25 January, the situation was not encouraging, given the closed nature of the cruise ship.

The diamond Princess, operated by Princess Cruises, a Cruise Company owned by Carnival Corporation & PLC, has five cabins: Inner, Ocean view, balcony, mini-suite and suite. Among them, there are no windows, narrow cabin accounted for 1 / 3 of the total number of cabins, other rooms of the viewing window embedded cabin, can not open.

On Feb. 6, a quarantined passenger stood on the balcony of his room. Photograph: AP

Many of the passengers were nervous and a little overwhelmed. With the Internet open, someone chooses to save the world via social media. Originally, in the cruise line is a fee-based service. After the outbreak of the disease inside the ship, the diamond princess opened up a free Internet service to passengers.

By Far, Davy Abel is probably the most talked about "celebrity passenger" on the ship. He is a wedding planner from the UK and is on board to celebrate his 50th wedding anniversary with his wife, Sally. Since Feb. 4, he has been streaming live video of the ship on Facebook, answering questions and asking viewers to share videos. As of February 13, he had released 50 videos with a total of more than 850,000 views.

As early as Jan. 30, Davy tried to check in with his family on Facebook. He sensed tension on the ship -- as if the crew had taken a variety of sanitary measures, including temperature readings, handwashing before meals, banning public toilets, and requiring passengers to sign a "face mask agreement. ".

But Davy and his wife never imagined the virus would get so close. When they crossed into Japan from Okinawa on February 1st, they found that a temperature check had been set up there, and all shore travel had been cancelled. It was not until two days later that Davy wrote on Facebook: "I didn't know this morning that there were more than 300 passengers boarding from Hong Kong, China, and one of them has been diagnosed with new pneumonia. " Davy had to cancel his flight home.

Two nights later, a captain's announcement broke the silence. The captain informed everyone that the Japanese medical staff would board and take the temperature of each passenger.

Medics in Hazmat suits leave the diamond princess. Photograph: Reuters

But this "screening" is also controversial. The Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare secretary, Katsunobu Kato, told a news conference on February 10th that they had not tested everyone on board for nucleic acids. Several Japanese media reports said the confirmed cases now being announced are from people judged to have symptoms such as fever and "close contacts" associated with them.

Some in the medical community question whether "close contact" is a strict medical definition. The term has appeared repeatedly in the Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare's guidelines for the prevention and control of pandemics. In a January 2007 Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare document for the new flu of the year, "close contacts" include cohabitants, health care workers involved in rescue operations, people exposed to contaminated material, and direct face-to-face contacts.

But there are still too many holes in the sieve for those on board. One Japanese passenger told Japanese television that they had only "filled out a health inquiry form" before two quarantine officers boarded the ship to take his temperature. Based on China's experience in prevention, control and Quarantine, many asymptomatic people end up testing positive for nucleic acids.

On the morning of February 4th, the quarantine officer was on the eighth floor of the cabin. Image via TWITTER@DAXA

There's obviously been some trouble on board. A video appeal for help, released on Feb. 5, brought Davy to public attention. In the video, he said he and his wife had not been fed for more than 14 hours and, as a diabetic, he could go into shock at any time. "I just want to know what happened! Any reporter who is watching this, please bring some news to the passengers and I will be very, very grateful, " Davy said at the end of the video.

Soon, more than 50,000 people had seen the message, and many had tried to contact the company for him. At the time, the Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare initially suspected the source of the virus was food, as the source of the virus had not yet been determined. Moreover, there were so many people on board that quarantine progress was much slower than they had expected. But Davy's situation was quickly resolved. Around 12:00 noon, the Davy arrived on the deck with a treat -- yogurt, orange juice, and diced cantaloupe -- Davy was diabetic and lactose intolerant, and the crew brought him bread rolls and butter.

Davy was one of the first passengers to take to social media to expose the inside of the ship, and his upbeat, talkative attitude and occasional jokes have earned him a lot of attention. He said in a live broadcast that he had been contacted by dozens of news media from the United States, Britain, Australia, Japan, China and New Zealand. He gave interviews to Britain's Daily Mail, Sky TV, ITV, the BBC and other media, the management of Princess cruises also approached him.

News sites are the number one source of information for passengers during the quarantine, who exchange and disseminate information on social media. Davy created a "princess in quarantine" group on Facebook to exchange information and block access to the media. As at 12 February, there were 93 members. "It was like we were the only ones who were kept in the dark, " he recalled. "shortly after the quarantine began, one of the passengers sent me a message saying that there had been a confirmed case in his country's news, and we just knew what was going on. "

UPDATES, food supplies, medical supplies, in-flight passengers are all issues of concern to netizens. In a video posted Feb. 6, Davy says meals are back on schedule; under medical supervision, passengers can take turns on deck for 90 minutes -- the deck is long -- as they wind down the aisles and circle back and forth. Another Japanese passenger also said the passengers could take turns on the deck for air, taking about three days at a time.

Delta passengers moving about on deck. Image via TWITTER@DAXA

However, Princess does not have the lead, they are not responsible for quarantine, and all data related to new crown pneumonia are released by the Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare. On February 7, Davy received a mask from the Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare, the first he had ever received on a cruise ship.

We may not have enough. Getting the drugs, however, is not an easy task. A Japanese passenger using the Twitter account@nsk061608 tried to call on Twitter -- as if she were on a quest so specific that she wouldn't even answer any other questions -- as if she had been given the medicine she needed for her chronic illness for five days. She had called the Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare, been pushed to the cruise infirmary, and contacted the front desk, only to learn that the infirmary had given priority to medicines for middle aged and elderly passengers. After submitting two drug requests, she finally received a 14-day dose after tweeting again for help.

Another 54-year-old Japanese passenger told Japan's Asahi Shimbun newspaper that she had a fever of 38.5 degrees Celsius, joint pain, flu and other symptoms, and waited more than three hours after making an appointment at the ship's infirmary, got a cold medicine for the flu. She was worried about being infected, but the infirmary rejected her request for a virus test as "not an emergency" .

On February 8, the cruise ship docked at the grand black terminal in Yokohama. In addition to cigarettes, alcohol and electrical products, the outside world can mail goods to passengers or hand them over to the reception desk of the terminal. The medicines are subject to a second inspection by the medical staff, and the remaining items can be loaded onto the ship after being inspected at the reception desk. The ship, which normally calls at Yokohama, made two trips to the high seas on February 5 and 8 to replenish its water supply by distilling sea water. The Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare sent helicopters and boats to follow.

A cruise ship moored at Yokohama port. Photograph: NBC News

On February 9, ambulances and fire engines parked in the port car park. Photo: Gay & Phil Courter

Most of the passengers who spoke out had demands of their own, including Davy. He had four demands: First, that information be made public and that no second hand information be obtained from news websites; second, that the period of isolation be extended as the number of confirmed cases increases; and third, that the Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare's response be inadequate, he said, in the past week they have been in limbo -- no health checks, no routine questions, no clear instructions on how to monitor the condition of the more than 2,000 passengers on board -- and trying to get in touch with the Home Office, to be informed of the post-return arrangements, including whether he and his family will need to be separated for two weeks.

As of February 13, neither the Home Office nor the Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare had spoken to him.

On Feb. 4, American Passenger Katherine Codekas and friends decided to cancel their plans to continue their trip to Shanghai and return directly to the United States from Japan. What really freaked her out was knowing she was being quarantined. "I realized we were going to be stuck on a boat, and this cabin was going to be our home for the next two weeks, " she said. She and her friends canceled their planned return, knowing they would not be able to go home for at least the next two weeks.

Even more worrisome to Catherine was the fact that they didn't know whether, after 14 days, they could be released from quarantine as long as they didn't have any symptoms of infection. "There's a lot of chatter online, and we're hoping for a definitive statement. "

Michael Ryan, who's executive director of the WHO's emergency health planning, said Feb. 7 that the quarantine period would be renewed if new infections were found on board. In addition, close contacts of the patient will be re-monitored.

To calm the passengers, the ship has started to provide psychological counseling by phone, but Davy still told netizens that he and his wife are eating less and less. Some Japanese passengers began to complain that most of the food on board was American, but they wanted something lighter.

The meal menu on the Delta Boat. Image via TWITTER@DAXA

The psychological hotline on the Diamond Princess. Photo: Gay & Phil Courter

The Australians on board have begun to fend for themselves. On Feb. 8, a Facebook group called Get Them off the Diamond Princess was formed. A total of 445 members of the team were made up of Australian passengers, journalists and family seekers. People started writing to the Australian consulate in Tokyo and to the prime minister, and the consulate was the most responsive. On February 8th Alana Donaldson of Alana Donneson, an Australian passenger, published an email response from the consulate to the effect that the ship was under Japanese jurisdiction and had no jurisdiction over it.

On Feb. 9, a Qantas 747 took off from Wuhan, carrying more than 200 Australians home. The Australian evacuation flight has raised expectations among Australians aboard the diamond princess that the government will help them leave the "floating prison" . In the past two days, some of the group members have also launched a petition on the social change.org  website titled "Take Them Home! " And as of the afternoon of February 12, only 143 people had signed.

The group's founder, Vera Koslova-Fu, said in a post that she had turned down requests for interviews from many members of the media, and had no intention of recording her life on video like Davy, an Internet celebrity on board. "sharing publicly makes me feel depressed, " said Villa, who also did not decide to reveal the group, which she started with a close former colleague, because the idea was simply to get the Australian citizens on board home safely.

Many passengers are actively liaising with the media. The American couple, Gay and Philip Courter, used Google's cloud to make their daily observations public, recording their status and needs. They are novelists and filmmakers, both in their 80s, and a son and daughter on a media-outreach mission.

Mr. and Mrs. Court's Cabin, a suite overlooking the harbor. Photo: Gay & Phil Courter

Just days before the ship became a "sea jail, " the diamond princess organized a dance competition in which each passenger randomly matched partners. The ballroom was a riot of lights, red faces, and crazy dancing. The Court's son tweeted angrily, "RANDOM PARTNERS! " It now appears that this may indeed be one reason for the spread of the infection.

The Court'balconies are relatively open, offering views of the sea and the harbor near Yokohama. Since the quarantine, they've been keeping a close eye on the vehicles. Two exits are being opened, and a blue curtain supports two long corridors. Even so, the 14-day quarantine will have to be counted out.

The balcony of the Court's room. Photo: Gay & Phil Courter

On February 10, the crew covered the gangway of the diamond princess with Tarpaulin. Photograph: AP

They put up a post-it and crossed off the days they spent. Behind the marked 19 is the three question mark, as if 19, the date on which the diamond princess is currently scheduled to be released from quarantine, and at this point, it's hard for them to predict what will happen. "We all think it's pretty black comedy, " she laughs about gay, who wrote a mystery novel about a cruise ship murder

The Court used a post-it note to keep track of time. Photo: Gay & Phil Courter

The Court were also worried about the rest of the ship. On February 7th, "We want to thank the crew for their tireless service, " they wrote on Google cloud. And, more importantly, we think they're at risk because they live in more crowded dormitories. These people are contracted into the service industry, have never had medical training and can not work in potentially contagious environments like professionals."

Passengers posted a thank-you note to the cruise staff on the door. Image via Twitter@Tony  

Their fears have come true. The crowded, airless space was indeed a virus-infected "hotbed" -- a ship with more than 1,000 crew members living below deck in an inner chamber, four sharing a bathroom and dining in a dining hall. Most of these people are from India, the Philippines, Indonesia, Sri Lanka, Ukraine and other countries.

印度籍船员比拿・库玛・萨卡（Binay Kumar Sarkar）是钻石公主号的厨房炊事员。他在 Facebook 视频里说：“医护人员只拿走了 500 多个样本，他们也只检测体温超过 37.5 度的人。”他呼吁印度政府和联合国采取行动，无论是隔离、撤侨都可以，他们只想平安回家。

With the exception of Pena, few sailors were willing to go public -- as if they feared losing their jobs. Two crew members were warned for expressing emotions on social media. One cabin attendant, who asked not to be named, told Futurogram that he was now working 12 hours a day, with a three-hour lunch break at noon, and that the company promised to pay him three times his salary for the days in isolation.

"We are not allowed to communicate with passengers, we only get information from the news, and everyone can only 'rest assured' , " another crew member, who spoke to the Ukrainian newspaper KP, said, "alcohol costs money, at $30 for 50ML, which is very expensive, but the food is free for everyone. The Japanese government says they will bring more food. "

These employees do not have protective clothing, usually only wear masks and disposable gloves. The Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare said the risk of infection was low because the crew could not come into contact with passengers.

The Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare clarified at a press conference that its top priority was to deal with drugs. In addition to medicines, they will work with local governments to provide them to passengers on cruise ships.

American passenger Matthew Smith posted on Twitter all the types of masks he has received so far. Image via Twitter@mjswhitebread  

Things took a turn for the worse on February 12th. The same day, a Yokohama Quarantine officer also confirmed the infection. He was quarantined from the night of February 3 to the night of February 4. His duties included collecting questionnaires, taking the temperature of passengers and entering the passenger cabin. He wore a mask and gloves, but did not wear protective clothing and goggles.

In response, the Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare said the measures followed guidelines from the World Health Organization (WHO) . The infection quarantine officer remained at his normal duty from 5 February to 7 February, with fever on 9 February and a medical diagnosis on 10 February.

According to data released by the Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare on February 13, the diamond princess carried 3,711 passengers, 2,666 passengers and 1,045 crew members. A total of 713 people were examined and 218 were diagnosed. These confirmed cases have been transferred to the Japanese medical institutions for treatment. A total of 33 people were confirmed in Japan, including 12 evacuees. The total number of confirmed cases in Japan rose to 251.

The diamond princess is also the first cluster infection outside China. Passengers are taking part in a 16-day "early spring cruise to Southeast Asia" that will cost between 250,000 yen (16,000 yuan) and 1,382,000 yen (88,000 yuan) each.

There are plenty of cruise ships on the high seas of Asia, and these days they could also be high risk areas for the virus. According to the Ministry of Land, Infrastructure, Transport and Tourism, foreign cruises planned to make 123 port calls in Japan in February have dropped to 75. In addition, many cruise ships passing through China have been denied entry to ports in several countries and have had to change their sailing plans.

The Cruise Lines International Association said passengers or crew members traveling through China or showing signs of illness will be refused boarding within 14 days of the ship's departure, the member companies monitor the health of the passengers. The association has more than 50 cruise company members and operates 95% of the world's cruise lines.

Princess cruises confirmed to the map of the future on February 9 that the Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare has now formed a professional medical team of 16 doctors, 12 nurses and medical receptionists, and arranged for more than 600 doses of medicine to be delivered to the ship, 7,000 respirators. According to the Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare, they received more than 1,700 requests from passengers, depending on the level of urgency.

Now, the quarantine team to check elderly passengers and people with symptoms of fever, such as more detailed standards, the ship provided mask has been upgraded to N95 level. At a press conference on February 10th Katsunobu Kato, the Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare minister, said he was considering introducing private testing companies and university bodies to increase the scope of testing. "It is difficult to test everyone at the moment, " admits Chief Cabinet Secretary Yoshihide Suga

Katsunobu Kato also said that the existence of "implementation mechanism reasons" , coupled with the need to consider other areas in case of an outbreak of treatment, the cruise ship can not be inspected. But he stressed that, in order to prevent the spread of infection, is considering for all but a part of the crew on board the virus test.

On February 7, the COVID-19 released a report on the evaluation of the current situation of infectious diseases in Japan and the preparation of the country's surveillance and medical mechanisms, it puts forward various benchmarks including testing mechanism, medical mechanism, diagnosis strategy, doubtful strategy, discharge standard and so on. The possibility of "false negative" in clinical practice has also increased the complexity of the detection process.

The corresponding process of SARS-CoV-2 infection patients put forward by the National Infection Research Institute of Japan. Image: National Institute of Infection

According to the Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare, there are currently between 1,500 and 2,000 daily detections of the virus in Japan. "It is not possible to say that all the tests were used on the cruise ship due to the problem of returning overseas Chinese and other reasons, " Japanese television quoted a staff member at the Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare as saying

There may be a new solution. On February 12th, during a focus session of the Budget Committee of Japan's Lower House of parliament, Katsunobu Kato went further, arguing that there is a risk of transmission of the virus from an infected person on land, the hope is to "speed up the discussion of 'hospital ships' equipped with inspection and treatment functions" . At present, Japan does not have a state-owned "hospital ship" , but Japan Maritime Self-defense Force and other institutions have a small number of "hospital ship" , as well as a number of patients can be admitted to set up operating tables of the ship. As at 11 February, a total of 16 passengers and crew members had disembarked for treatment due to pneumonia or other illnesses. As of Feb. 13, about 3,000 people had not been tested for the virus.

The Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare announced new measures on February 13th: A new round of testing will start with vulnerable people, such as passengers over 80. Passengers whose test results are negative, who live in rooms with no windows and windows that can not be opened, or who have underlying illnesses, may disembark from February 14 as they wish, to a quarantine facility prepared by the government.

The quarantine of the diamond princess is tentatively set to end on February 19th, although fears of further spread of the virus on the ship have repeatedly surfaced on social media.

Yaroslav Kulish, a reporter for the Ukrainian newspaper KP, contributed to this report

Among them, there are no windows, narrow cabin accounted for 1 / 3 of the total number of cabins, other rooms of the viewing window embedded cabin, can not open.

By Far, Davy Abel is probably the most talked about "celebrity passenger" on the ship. He is a wedding planner from the UK and is on board to celebrate his 50th wedding anniversary with his wife, Sally. Since Feb. 4, he has been streaming live video of the ship on Facebook, answering questions and asking viewers to share videos. As of February 13, he had released 50 videos with a total of more than 850,000 views.

As early as Jan. 30, Davy tried to check in with his family on Facebook. He sensed tension on the ship -- as if the crew had taken a variety of sanitary measures, including temperature readings, handwashing before meals, banning public toilets, and requiring passengers to sign a "face mask agreement. ".

But Davy and his wife never imagined the virus would get so close. When they crossed into Japan from Okinawa on February 1st, they found that a temperature check had been set up there, and all shore travel had been cancelled. " Davy had to cancel his flight home.

But this "screening" is also controversial. The Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare secretary, Katsunobu Kato, told a news conference on February 10th that they had not tested everyone on board for nucleic acids. Several Japanese media reports said the confirmed cases now being announced are from people judged to have symptoms such as fever and "close contacts" associated with them.

Some in the medical community question whether "close contact" is a strict medical definition. The term has appeared repeatedly in the Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare's guidelines for the prevention and control of pandemics. In a January 2007 Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare document for the new flu of the year, "close contacts" include cohabitants, health care workers involved in rescue operations, people exposed to contaminated material, and direct face-to-face contacts.

But there are still too many holes in the sieve for those on board. One Japanese passenger told Japanese television that they had only "filled out a health inquiry form" before two quarantine officers boarded the ship to take his temperature. Based on China's experience in prevention, control and Quarantine, many asymptomatic people end up testing positive for nucleic acids.

Things took a turn for the worse on February 12th. The same day, a Yokohama Quarantine officer also confirmed the infection. He was quarantined from the night of February 3 to the night of February 4. His duties included collecting questionnaires, taking the temperature of passengers and entering the passenger cabin. He wore a mask and gloves, but did not wear protective clothing and goggles.

In response, the Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare said the measures followed guidelines from the World Health Organization (WHO) . The infection quarantine officer remained at his normal duty from 5 February to 7 February, with fever on 9 February and a medical diagnosis on 10 February.

According to data released by the Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare on February 13, the diamond princess carried 3,711 passengers, 2,666 passengers and 1,045 crew members. A total of 713 people were examined and 218 were diagnosed. These confirmed cases have been transferred to the Japanese medical institutions for treatment. A total of 33 people were confirmed in Japan, including 12 evacuees. The total number of confirmed cases in Japan rose to 251.

The diamond princess is also the first cluster infection outside China. Passengers are taking part in a 16-day "early spring cruise to Southeast Asia" that will cost between 250,000 yen (16,000 yuan) and 1,382,000 yen (88,000 yuan) each.

There are plenty of cruise ships on the high seas of Asia, and these days they could also be high risk areas for the virus. According to the Ministry of Land, Infrastructure, Transport and Tourism, foreign cruises planned to make 123 port calls in Japan in February have dropped to 75. In addition, many cruise ships passing through China have been denied entry to ports in several countries and have had to change their sailing plans.

The Cruise Lines International Association said passengers or crew members traveling through China or showing signs of illness will be refused boarding within 14 days of the ship's departure, the member companies monitor the health of the passengers. The association has more than 50 cruise company members and operates 95% of the world's cruise lines.

Princess cruises confirmed to the map of the future on February 9 that the Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare has now formed a professional medical team of 16 doctors, 12 nurses and medical receptionists, and arranged for more than 600 doses of medicine to be delivered to the ship, 7,000 respirators. According to the Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare, they received more than 1,700 requests from passengers, depending on the level of urgency.

Now, the quarantine team to check elderly passengers and people with symptoms of fever, such as more detailed standards, the ship provided mask has been upgraded to N95 level. At a press conference on February 10th Katsunobu Kato, the Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare minister, said he was considering introducing private testing companies and university bodies to increase the scope of testing. "It is difficult to test everyone at the moment, " admits Chief Cabinet Secretary Yoshihide Suga

Katsunobu Kato also said that the existence of "implementation mechanism reasons" , coupled with the need to consider other areas in case of an outbreak of treatment, the cruise ship can not be inspected. But he stressed that, in order to prevent the spread of infection, is considering for all but a part of the crew on board the virus test.

On February 7, the COVID-19 released a report on the evaluation of the current situation of infectious diseases in Japan and the preparation of the country's surveillance and medical mechanisms, it puts forward various benchmarks including testing mechanism, medical mechanism, diagnosis strategy, doubtful strategy, discharge standard and so on. The possibility of "false negative" in clinical practice has also increased the complexity of the detection process.

The corresponding process of SARS-CoV-2 infection patients put forward by the National Infection Research Institute of Japan. Image: National Institute of Infection

According to the Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare, there are currently between 1,500 and 2,000 daily detections of the virus in Japan. "It is not possible to say that all the tests were used on the cruise ship due to the problem of returning overseas Chinese and other reasons, " Japanese television quoted a staff member at the Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare as saying

There may be a new solution. On February 12th, during a focus session of the Budget Committee of Japan's Lower House of parliament, Katsunobu Kato went further, arguing that there is a risk of transmission of the virus from an infected person on land, the hope is to "speed up the discussion of 'hospital ships' equipped with inspection and treatment functions" . At present, Japan does not have a state-owned "hospital ship" , but Japan Maritime Self-defense Force and other institutions have a small number of "hospital ship" , as well as a number of patients can be admitted to set up operating tables of the ship. As at 11 February, a total of 16 passengers and crew members had disembarked for treatment due to pneumonia or other illnesses. As of Feb. 13, about 3,000 people had not been tested for the virus.

The Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare announced new measures on February 13th: A new round of testing will start with vulnerable people, such as passengers over 80. Passengers whose test results are negative, who live in rooms with no windows and windows that can not be opened, or who have underlying illnesses, may disembark from February 14 as they wish, to a quarantine facility prepared by the government.

The quarantine of the diamond princess is tentatively set to end on February 19th, although fears of further spread of the virus on the ship have repeatedly surfaced on social media.

Things took a turn for the worse on February 12th. The same day, a Yokohama Quarantine officer also confirmed the infection. He was quarantined from the night of February 3 to the night of February 4. His duties included collecting questionnaires, taking the temperature of passengers and entering the passenger cabin. He wore a mask and gloves, but did not wear protective clothing and goggles.

In response, the Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare said the measures followed guidelines from the World Health Organization (WHO) . The infection quarantine officer remained at his normal duty from 5 February to 7 February, with fever on 9 February and a medical diagnosis on 10 February.

According to data released by the Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare on February 13, the diamond princess carried 3,711 passengers, 2,666 passengers and 1,045 crew members. A total of 713 people were examined and 218 were diagnosed. These confirmed cases have been transferred to the Japanese medical institutions for treatment. A total of 33 people were confirmed in Japan, including 12 evacuees. The total number of confirmed cases in Japan rose to 251.

The diamond princess is also the first cluster infection outside China. Passengers are taking part in a 16-day "early spring cruise to Southeast Asia" that will cost between 250,000 yen (16,000 yuan) and 1,382,000 yen (88,000 yuan) each.

There are plenty of cruise ships on the high seas of Asia, and these days they could also be high risk areas for the virus. According to the Ministry of Land, Infrastructure, Transport and Tourism, foreign cruises planned to make 123 port calls in Japan in February have dropped to 75. In addition, many cruise ships passing through China have been denied entry to ports in several countries and have had to change their sailing plans.

The Cruise Lines International Association said passengers or crew members traveling through China or showing signs of illness will be refused boarding within 14 days of the ship's departure, the member companies monitor the health of the passengers. The association has more than 50 cruise company members and operates 95% of the world's cruise lines.

Princess cruises confirmed to the map of the future on February 9 that the Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare has now formed a professional medical team of 16 doctors, 12 nurses and medical receptionists, and arranged for more than 600 doses of medicine to be delivered to the ship, 7,000 respirators. According to the Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare, they received more than 1,700 requests from passengers, depending on the level of urgency.

Now, the quarantine team to check elderly passengers and people with symptoms of fever, such as more detailed standards, the ship provided mask has been upgraded to N95 level. At a press conference on February 10th Katsunobu Kato, the Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare minister, said he was considering introducing private testing companies and university bodies to increase the scope of testing. "It is difficult to test everyone at the moment, " admits Chief Cabinet Secretary Yoshihide Suga

Katsunobu Kato also said that the existence of "implementation mechanism reasons" , coupled with the need to consider other areas in case of an outbreak of treatment, the cruise ship can not be inspected. But he stressed that, in order to prevent the spread of infection, is considering for all but a part of the crew on board the virus test.

On February 7, the COVID-19 released a report on the evaluation of the current situation of infectious diseases in Japan and the preparation of the country's surveillance and medical mechanisms, it puts forward various benchmarks including testing mechanism, medical mechanism, diagnosis strategy, doubtful strategy, discharge standard and so on. The possibility of "false negative" in clinical practice has also increased the complexity of the detection process.
